    "summary": "The fall of the Western Roman Empire (conventionally dated to 476 AD when [[event:2861|Odoacer Deposes Romulus]] deposed the last emperor Romulus Augustulus) was a process stretching over centuries rather than a single event — the gradual unraveling of Roman political authority in the West through a combination of economic strain, military overextension, political fragmentation, the [[event:2038|Germanic Migration Period]] Germanic migrations, and the loss of fiscal and administrative coherence. The event has generated one of history's longest historiographical debates: Edward Gibbon's 18th-century attribution of decline to Christianity and barbarian invasions began a controversy that continues today.\n\nThe [[event:2025|Crisis of Third Century]] (235–284 AD) nearly destroyed the empire; [[event:2026|Diocletian Reforms]] and [[event:2027|Constantine the Great]] stabilized it temporarily through radical administrative restructuring and the [[event:2790|Division Roman Empire]]. But the [[event:2793|Battle of Adrianople]] (378 AD), where the Visigoths killed the Emperor Valens, showed the military's vulnerability. The [[event:2033|Sack of Rome by Visigoths]] (410 AD) shocked the empire's psychological self-confidence; the [[event:2037|Vandal Sack of Rome]] (455 AD) further stripped resources. By 476 AD, the Western imperial title had become meaningless — power rested with Germanic military commanders, and its formal abolition changed little practically. The Eastern Empire (Byzantine) survived the process intact, viewing itself as the legitimate continuation of Rome.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fall_of_the_Western_Roman_Empire",
